00:48:52.090 --> 00:48:54.140
versus measurables
and all of that.

00:48:54.140 --> 00:48:58.650
But you know, when you compare
money against happiness,

00:48:58.650 --> 00:49:03.830
it turns out happiness is
really difficult to pursue.

00:49:03.830 --> 00:49:07.480
In many cases, money can
sometimes be easier to pursue.

00:49:07.480 --> 00:49:09.595
Or at least you know when
you're making progress.

00:49:13.310 --> 00:49:16.980
So as a parent, when I
look at my own experience--

00:49:16.980 --> 00:49:20.090
and at Google, everybody
says, oh, be curious.

00:49:20.090 --> 00:49:21.330
This is a different company.

00:49:21.330 --> 00:49:23.440
It's not your normal company.

00:49:23.440 --> 00:49:26.640
But the way they
let me in here is

00:49:26.640 --> 00:49:30.850
through some pretty
rigorous testing.

00:49:30.850 --> 00:49:33.870
And I worry about
that for my own kid,

00:49:33.870 --> 00:49:35.760
especially now
that I'm at Google.

00:49:35.760 --> 00:49:36.450
Oh, be Googly.

00:49:36.450 --> 00:49:37.430
Have fun.

00:49:37.430 --> 00:49:37.930
Do this.

00:49:37.930 --> 00:49:38.930
Do that.

00:49:38.930 --> 00:49:43.640
And you know, that's
not how I grew up.

00:49:43.640 --> 00:49:45.400
You know, there were
standardized tests.

00:49:45.400 --> 00:49:47.110
And I did well at them.

00:49:47.110 --> 00:49:49.780
And you know, I'm at
a point in my life

00:49:49.780 --> 00:49:52.750
where I can be as
Googly as I want.

00:49:52.750 --> 00:49:55.944
But is that the right
thing to teach my child?

00:49:55.944 --> 00:49:56.610
SUSAN ENGEL: Oh.

00:49:56.610 --> 00:50:00.030
What a great question.

00:50:00.030 --> 00:50:03.110
Well, first of all,
I don't know you.

00:50:03.110 --> 00:50:04.730
So I don't know
all the qualities

00:50:04.730 --> 00:50:10.130
that made you Googly-- a phrase
I never knew until just now.

00:50:10.130 --> 00:50:12.670
But this is not everything.

00:50:12.670 --> 00:50:16.040
So intelligence is
something important.

00:50:16.040 --> 00:50:19.670
And it's something by and
large you're born with.

00:50:19.670 --> 00:50:23.860
Though without
certain privileges

00:50:23.860 --> 00:50:27.830
like stability and
health and basic needs

00:50:27.830 --> 00:50:29.560
met when you're
little, you don't

00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:32.670
get to fulfill your
intellectual capacity.

00:50:32.670 --> 00:50:35.140
That's why we see
big class differences

00:50:35.140 --> 00:50:37.430
in terms of the measure
of intelligence,

00:50:37.430 --> 00:50:41.600
because if you have good
food and a same house

00:50:41.600 --> 00:50:43.930
to go to every night
and conversations,

00:50:43.930 --> 00:50:46.620
you will fulfill your
intellectual capacity more

00:50:46.620 --> 00:50:47.830
than another kid.

00:50:47.830 --> 00:50:49.780
But even so, some
people are going

00:50:49.780 --> 00:50:51.250
to be smarter than others.

00:50:51.250 --> 00:50:54.790
And maybe it's true that Google
hires the smartest people.

00:50:54.790 --> 00:50:57.040
And that's going to
be true-- I mean,

00:50:57.040 --> 00:50:58.570
maybe that's why you got hired.

00:50:58.570 --> 00:51:00.110
And maybe that's
why you did well

00:51:00.110 --> 00:51:01.650
on some of standardized tests.

00:51:01.650 --> 00:51:05.770
So I'm not negating that.

00:51:05.770 --> 00:51:08.770
But there are also
many people who are not

00:51:08.770 --> 00:51:10.070
going to work at Google.

00:51:10.070 --> 00:51:12.220
And it may be wonderful here.

00:51:12.220 --> 00:51:15.110
I may be incredible
to be Googly.

00:51:15.110 --> 00:51:18.090
But it's not the
only place to work,

00:51:18.090 --> 00:51:20.630
and it's not the
only way to be happy.

00:51:20.630 --> 00:51:22.760
It would be very
cool-- maybe you've

00:51:22.760 --> 00:51:27.960
done it-- to do some measures
of whether people who work here

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:31.300
are happier in their lives.

00:51:31.300 --> 00:51:35.220
That part's going to get
cut out of the video.

00:51:35.220 --> 00:51:37.880
REGINA: I smile because
we look at [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:37.880 --> 00:51:38.630
SUSAN ENGEL: Good.

00:51:38.630 --> 00:51:40.470
I'd love to know more about it.

00:51:40.470 --> 00:51:42.349
And you know, when I
use the word "happy"--

00:51:42.349 --> 00:51:44.640
and I take great pains in
the book to talk about this--

00:51:44.640 --> 00:51:46.850
I'm not talking
about having fun.

00:51:46.850 --> 00:51:48.830
So I tell a story in
the book about when

00:51:48.830 --> 00:51:53.040
my children were little and a
little kid came over to play.

00:51:53.040 --> 00:51:56.110
And his mother went home
and told his mother,

00:51:56.110 --> 00:51:57.720
let's play Susan and Jake.

00:51:57.720 --> 00:51:59.270
That was my eldest boy.

00:51:59.270 --> 00:52:01.475
And she said, how do
you play Susan and Jake?

00:52:01.475 --> 00:52:03.000
And he said, you be Susan.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:05.070
And you keep saying,
want a lollipop?

00:52:05.070 --> 00:52:08.720
And that's not what I have
in mind for happiness.

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:11.050
I mean finding fulfillment,
finding meaning,

00:52:11.050 --> 00:52:13.230
working with others.

00:52:13.230 --> 00:52:15.220
Like I said, seeking
knowledge, being

00:52:15.220 --> 00:52:17.180
able to be thoughtful
about things.

00:52:17.180 --> 00:52:21.740
I think actually if schools
were to seriously focus

00:52:21.740 --> 00:52:25.300
on those things, not
just pay lip service,

00:52:25.300 --> 00:52:26.650
I don't know what Googly means.

00:52:26.650 --> 00:52:27.510
Now I want to know.

00:52:27.510 --> 00:52:31.340
But if it's just a
phrase, it's not much.

00:52:31.340 --> 00:52:34.110
If it captures something
serious about the way

00:52:34.110 --> 00:52:37.170
people do things here, well
I'm thinking of something

00:52:37.170 --> 00:52:38.150
similar in schools.

00:52:38.150 --> 00:52:41.600
And I'm guessing that if kids
did those things in schools,

00:52:41.600 --> 00:52:44.320
many more of them would
be well-equipped to work

00:52:44.320 --> 00:52:47.291
environments like this.

00:52:47.291 --> 00:52:47.790
Yeah.

00:52:47.790 --> 00:52:49.779
REGINA: That's one more
here in the corner.

00:52:49.779 --> 00:52:51.070
And then I think we're at time.

00:52:51.070 --> 00:52:54.100
And I'm going to sneak one
more question in and go over.

00:52:54.100 --> 00:52:55.920
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:52:55.920 --> 00:52:57.740
First of all, I really
like what you're

00:52:57.740 --> 00:53:01.276
talking about as the training
for happiness and curiosity

00:53:01.276 --> 00:53:02.150
and things like that.

00:53:02.150 --> 00:53:03.730
I've seen it in my own children.

00:53:03.730 --> 00:53:08.300
We had to take some out of
school because the way they

00:53:08.300 --> 00:53:11.070
were taught just wasn't--
we teach them from home.

00:53:11.070 --> 00:53:14.170
And believe me, even if
I've encouraged them, hey,

00:53:14.170 --> 00:53:18.620
I want you to go into something
so I can live off of you,

00:53:18.620 --> 00:53:19.240
they're not.

00:53:19.240 --> 00:53:23.555
They all seem to be going
art or social type of things.

00:53:23.555 --> 00:53:24.680
SUSAN ENGEL: Good for them.

00:53:24.680 --> 00:53:26.810
AUDIENCE: Looking for
things that are happy.

00:53:26.810 --> 00:53:29.700
And I've also seen how
the curiosity or the love

00:53:29.700 --> 00:53:31.500
of learning is just
[INAUDIBLE] out based

00:53:31.500 --> 00:53:35.110
on a teacher, based
off of a textbook,

00:53:35.110 --> 00:53:37.700
and a way it's taught.

00:53:37.700 --> 00:53:41.380
So I see how that cripples them.

00:53:41.380 --> 00:53:44.240
My current 16-year-old
loves history,

00:53:44.240 --> 00:53:46.010
but hated social
studies last year,

00:53:46.010 --> 00:53:50.090
because the book
was frankly awful.

00:53:50.090 --> 00:53:55.510
But so I see this as
a positive direction.

00:53:55.510 --> 00:53:57.630
This is what we really need.

00:53:57.630 --> 00:54:02.390
But how do you do this
and keep the bureaucracy

00:54:02.390 --> 00:54:04.160
and the administration
out of it?

00:54:04.160 --> 00:54:08.250
Because I've seen a lot
of good educational ideas.

00:54:08.250 --> 00:54:09.920
But then they go
to the government

00:54:09.920 --> 00:54:12.930
and they put all this other
stuff in, and then by the time

00:54:12.930 --> 00:54:17.764
it gets back to the schools,
it's just a huge mess.

00:54:17.764 --> 00:54:19.430
And the teachers don't
have any control.

00:54:19.430 --> 00:54:21.330
And this sounds
like the teachers'

00:54:21.330 --> 00:54:23.390
got to have complete control.

00:54:23.390 --> 00:54:26.580
And you've got to really train
the teachers up very well

00:54:26.580 --> 00:54:28.330
in advance on how
to be doing this.

00:54:28.330 --> 00:54:29.830
It's not just
something you say, OK.

00:54:29.830 --> 00:54:30.910
We're going to now do it.

00:54:30.910 --> 00:54:31.576
SUSAN ENGEL: No.

00:54:31.576 --> 00:54:32.870
I think that's really true.

00:54:32.870 --> 00:54:35.050
And I think Regina
asked before about

00:54:35.050 --> 00:54:37.730
whether there are any
schools that are doing this.

00:54:37.730 --> 00:54:40.587
I think we are not making
use of the great models that

00:54:40.587 --> 00:54:41.170
are out there.

00:54:41.170 --> 00:54:44.150
There are schools
that are doing this.

00:54:44.150 --> 00:54:45.790
And it's not because
they're keeping

00:54:45.790 --> 00:54:47.010
administrators out of it.

00:54:47.010 --> 00:54:49.120
It's because they have
good administrators.

00:54:49.120 --> 00:54:52.010
And we just need
to build on that.

00:54:52.010 --> 00:54:54.000
The question about
government is way beyond

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:55.210
my area of expertise.

00:54:55.210 --> 00:54:57.290
You know, I'm such an optimist.

00:54:57.290 --> 00:55:00.400
So I'm thinking, oh,
just change their minds.

00:55:00.400 --> 00:55:01.170
But ha!

00:55:03.600 --> 00:55:08.922
So E. O. Wilson, who
is sort of famous,

00:55:08.922 --> 00:55:11.490
the most famous
biologist, really, alive,

00:55:11.490 --> 00:55:16.020
who really developed
the idea of biodiversity

00:55:16.020 --> 00:55:20.630
and is a powerful
spokesperson for ecology

00:55:20.630 --> 00:55:22.220
and for the environment.

00:55:22.220 --> 00:55:24.200
I was once listening
to him speak.

00:55:24.200 --> 00:55:27.740
And someone said-- and I
think he's near 90 now--

00:55:27.740 --> 00:55:31.590
and they said, faced with all
the problems with the way we

00:55:31.590 --> 00:55:34.450
treat the environment and all
the species that have died off,

00:55:34.450 --> 00:55:39.480
and all the problems, how do you
have the courage and the umph

00:55:39.480 --> 00:55:42.580
to go on promoting these
better practices on the Earth.

00:55:42.580 --> 00:55:44.670
And he said, what
choice do I have?

00:55:44.670 --> 00:55:45.730
What's the alternative?

00:55:45.730 --> 00:55:47.880
And I feel that way
about education.

00:55:47.880 --> 00:55:51.370
So it's been hard to change
the minds of administrators

00:55:51.370 --> 00:55:54.319
or to make schools-- that's
a whole other talk about how

00:55:54.319 --> 00:55:55.985
you create the
conditions in the school,

00:55:55.985 --> 00:55:58.120
and good teachers can be good.

00:55:58.120 --> 00:56:01.520
And I think there are
clear ways to do that.

00:56:01.520 --> 00:56:03.560
I don't get discouraged
or I don't give up

00:56:03.560 --> 00:56:05.500
because what choice do I have?

00:56:05.500 --> 00:56:08.490
So it's just a matter
of sticking with it

00:56:08.490 --> 00:56:10.520
until we make some progress.

00:56:10.520 --> 00:56:12.226
And making use of the
really good models

00:56:12.226 --> 00:56:13.350
that are already out there.

00:56:16.510 --> 00:56:17.885
REGINA: I'm just
going to squeeze

00:56:17.885 --> 00:56:21.020
in the whole-- I'm really
concerned about my kid getting

00:56:21.020 --> 00:56:22.140
into a good school.

00:56:22.140 --> 00:56:26.230
What about for that
question and concern?

00:56:26.230 --> 00:56:27.481
SUSAN ENGEL: Oh, boy oh boy.

00:56:27.481 --> 00:56:27.980
I have--

00:56:27.980 --> 00:56:28.900
REGINA: Especially college.

00:56:28.900 --> 00:56:29.340
SUSAN ENGEL: Yeah.

00:56:29.340 --> 00:56:30.070
Whoops.

00:56:30.070 --> 00:56:30.860
That's a loud one.

00:56:30.860 --> 00:56:31.480
That's OK.

00:56:31.480 --> 00:56:33.890
So I'm going to quote
another educator about this.

00:56:33.890 --> 00:56:35.556
Because he said
something that I thought

00:56:35.556 --> 00:56:39.970
was so beautifully put, that
I've got to borrow from him.

00:56:39.970 --> 00:56:41.000
His name is Alfie Kohn.

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:47.210
And he has said to groups
of people, how much damage

00:56:47.210 --> 00:56:49.870
are you willing to
do to your child

00:56:49.870 --> 00:56:53.490
to make sure they get into
a school that only appears

00:56:53.490 --> 00:56:56.900
to be a little bit better
than some other school?

00:56:56.900 --> 00:56:58.720
And what I mean
by that-- and I'm

00:56:58.720 --> 00:57:01.410
guessing it's particularly
relevant for this kind

00:57:01.410 --> 00:57:04.290
of a population--
is that this idea

00:57:04.290 --> 00:57:08.230
that there's only a few
really good schools is crazy.

00:57:08.230 --> 00:57:10.510
There are a lot of
really good schools.

00:57:10.510 --> 00:57:13.530
There are so many good,
bright young people with PhDs

00:57:13.530 --> 00:57:16.030
and they're not all at
Stanford, believe it or not.

00:57:16.030 --> 00:57:19.480
They're all over the country
at all kinds of universities

00:57:19.480 --> 00:57:22.600
and colleges, including
community colleges and state

00:57:22.600 --> 00:57:24.030
universities.

00:57:24.030 --> 00:57:27.000
The most important
thing is that your child

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:30.420
wants to go to school and wants
to go for the right reasons.

00:57:30.420 --> 00:57:33.960
And I teach at a very selective
college-- Williams College.

00:57:33.960 --> 00:57:37.160
And I can tell you
that they all benefit

00:57:37.160 --> 00:57:40.840
in the more conventional
ways from having that degree.

00:57:40.840 --> 00:57:42.790
But the ones that really
benefit are the ones

00:57:42.790 --> 00:57:46.990
that actually are there to be
educated, and take something

00:57:46.990 --> 00:57:50.140
out of college more than
just the piece of paper.

00:57:50.140 --> 00:57:52.790
And that's what parents
should be thinking about.

00:57:54.922 --> 00:57:57.380
REGINA: Well, I'm going to end
there just for the recording

00:57:57.380 --> 00:57:57.870
standpoint.

00:57:57.870 --> 00:57:59.370
Susan's going to
be available after.

00:57:59.370 --> 00:58:02.300
Thank you everyone
for joining us.

